\f0\b\fs44 \cf2 What This Book Is, and What It Is For
\f1\b0\fs28 \cf2 \
\
A democracy is not a machine that runs on its own. It requires care, attention, and a shared understanding of what it is meant to accomplish. When those elements fade, a nation can keep the appearance of self-government long after the substance has begun to erode. The United States has entered a period in which the forms of democracy still exist, but the foundations beneath them have weakened. The purpose of this book is to help rebuild those foundations.\
\
This is not a book about personalities or parties. It is not a chronicle of grievances, nor a catalogue of political sins. It is a guide to something far more important: the conditions a democracy must meet in order to function, the obligations it must fulfill in order to survive, and the work the American people can do\'97this year\'97to repair what has been damaged and renew what has been neglected.\
\
Across the past decade, the country has learned a hard truth: institutions do not protect themselves. Courts, agencies, legislative bodies, and the civil service depend on norms of honesty, restraint, and stewardship. When leaders ignore those norms, the public must decide whether to defend them or permit their collapse. When the information ecosystem fractures, citizens must determine whether they will seek truth or reward manipulation. When government ceases to deliver fairness and opportunity, voters must choose whether to demand better or settle for less.\
\
These choices cannot be outsourced. They cannot be delegated. In a democracy, the people are the ultimate custodians of the system. The moment they stop insisting on integrity, the moment they stop expecting institutions to function, the moment they withdraw from the responsibilities of citizenship, the system begins to drift toward something else\'97something narrower, more brittle, less accountable, and less free.\
\
The United States has reached a point where the question before it is no longer whether democracy is ideal, but whether democracy is essential. The answer to that question will not be decided by any single leader or institution. It will be decided by the people themselves: by how they vote, how they organize, how they talk about their country, and how they hold power accountable. This book exists to help them do that work with clarity and confidence.\
\
