These concepts are not academic. They are the distilled principles of every democracy that has rebuilt itself after a period of backsliding\'97from postwar recoveries in Europe to the institutional reforms undertaken in dozens of countries over the past half-century. They are also consistent with the founding promises of the United States and the constitutional obligations still binding on its leaders.\
If this book has a thesis, it is this: 
\f2\b Democracy can be repaired\'97but not by accident, and not without a plan.
\f1\b0  It requires intentional action, informed by a clear understanding of what has been damaged and what must be restored. It requires the public to see itself not as an audience but as an active participant in the work of self-government. And it requires leaders willing to treat constitutional limits not as inconveniences but as commitments.\
The chapters ahead do not assume ideal conditions. They do not assume that trust will return overnight, that institutions will snap back to strength, or that political factions will suddenly find common purpose. They assume instead that democracy can be rebuilt the way democracies have always been rebuilt: by grounding the work in first principles, repairing structural weaknesses, restoring the state\'92s capacity to serve the public, and recommitting to the ethics that allow a free society to endure.\
This book is structured around that sequence.\
